Primitives
1   Variables
    A variable is a label for a location in memory where information is stored
	Python has three primitive types: numbers, strings and booleans
	Numbers can be integers or floating point (floats').
	Booleans are Capitalized.

*******************************************************************************
2   Variable names
    Use names that are descriptive, as in self documenting code.
	It is ok to use single letter variables for things where peole a accustomed to seeing a single letter.
	    Examples are coordinate points in a coordinate system or cell addresses in a matrix.
	Use all lower case lettersin words and seperate wordds with underscores.
	Formatting: Uses spaces between everything. Don't count on your formatter.

*******************************************************************************
3   Strings
    Strings are surrounded by quotes.
	Most people use double quotes.
	Mosh says some people use triple quotes around multi-line strings. Doesn't this conflict with the use of triple quotes for strings?
	A function is a reuseable piece of code
	Get the length of a string with "len(string_name)'.
	Get a letter from a string with it's index (position). If a_string = "python' then a_string[1] is 'y'.

*******************************************************************************
4   Escape Sequences
    \ is the 'escape character'
	\" is an 'escape sequence'
	Other common python escape sequences include \', \\ and \n
	
*******************************************************************************
5   Formatted Strings
    We can replace: full = first + " " + last, with full = f"{first}     {last}". The second is a formatted string. 
	
*******************************************************************************
6   String Methods
    Everything in python is an object.
	Objects have functions called methods.
	These methods return a new string, the old sttring remains.
	He goes over:
    	.upper,
		.lower,
		.title,
		.strip which removes leading or trailing white space which is useful for cleaning user input
		.rstrip removes whitespace from right
		.lstrip removes whitespace from left
		.find(arg) returns the start index of the arg or -1
		.replace
		and
		print("pro" in course) returns True
		print("swift" not in course) returns True

