Functions
1   Defining Functions
    The syntax to create a function:
	    def a_useful_function_name():
            # This is a line comment in python
		    """
			The line above is the beginning of a block comment in python.
			The line below is the end of a block comment in python.
			"""
			# All the indented line after the def statement belong to the new function


        According to pep8 there should be two blank lines between the end of
		    the function code and it's invocation.

******************************************************************************
2   Arguments
    A parameter is there ariable you need for your function to working.
	An argument is the value you give to it when you call the function.
	A function requires an argument to be sent for each parameter or it will not run.

******************************************************************************
3   Types of functions
    There are two types of functions:
	    functions that perform a task like print().
		Functions that return a value such as round().
	Functions that don't return a value return 'None'.
	Even thou it returns noone it is considered a function that performs a task.
	Mosh says a function that returns a value which can be saved in a variable
	    is more useful, 'better', than a function thatsimply performs a task.	

******************************************************************************
4   Keyword Arguments
    You can make the code more readable by including the keyword in the argument.
	    See the code.
	If you're not using keyword/named agruments you're using positional arguments.
	If you are using named arguments the position in the arg lsit does not matter.
	You can mix and match but there must be rules.
	Using named arguments means you can leave out some agrs esp default ones.
	https://treyhunner.com/2018/04/keyword-arguments-in-python/

******************************************************************************
5   Default Arguments
    If you set a default value for an arg in the function definition then when
	   you make the function call you don't need to supply that arg unless it
	   is different from the default.

******************************************************************************
6   xargs
    How to pass a variable number of arguments
    Use a plural name for multiple arguments to show there are more than one.
	Precede the multiple arguments name with an asterisk.
	If you print your arguments you get a tuple.
	A tuple is similar to a list but you cannot modify a tuple and a tuple has
	    parentheses instead of square brackets.
	Tuples re iterable.

******************************************************************************
7   xxargs
    Use **args to pass multiple key:value pairs.
	When you print **args you get a dictionary.
	It looks like '*' might be called the 'iterable unpacking operator'
	    and '**' is the 'dictionary unpacking operator' if Iunderstand
		PEP8 correctly.
		Just call them 'unpacing operator' or even 'asterisk'.
	Also, someone on SO said they're not really operators but '*' and '**' 
	    are used elsewhere for some completely different
		reason (overloading) where they are operators.
	See: https://www.educba.com/python-operators/ fotr a definition of and
	    discussion about, operators.

******************************************************************************
8   Scope
    If you create a variable inside a function it is a local variable. 6:17:40...6:24:57 7:17 sump pump
	    It has no life outside the function.
		The same is true for function parameters.
	If you create a variable in a file outside of any function it is a 
	    global variable. These are to be avoided.
	You can have function parameters and variables with the same names in 
	    different functions.
	Use the expression 'global variable_name' to refer to a global variable 
	    inside a function. EXCEPT DON'T DO IT.
	Do not modify global variable inside functions.

******************************************************************************
9   Debugging
    Create code and discover it needs debugging.
	Press the debug icon in vscode.
	Create the launch.json file by clicking the blue text and ignoring the
	    'add configuration' button.
	Move the cursor to the line where you want to start debugging and enter
	    Fn+F9 to add/remove breakpoint.
	Use Fn+F10 to step to the next line.
	Use Fn+F11 to step into a function. Use shft+Fn+F11 to step out of a function
	Wether or not the debugger warns you of undeclared vars in the watch panel
	    must be a setting Mosh set in his vscode.
	Stop the debugger with shift+Fn+F5.
	When you step from one line to the next The variables update as required by
        the code of the line left.

******************************************************************************
10  VSCode Tricks for Windows
    Use ctrl+Home and ctrl+End to move as you'd expect in vscode.
	Use shft+alt+down_arrow to copt a line downward.
