##############################################################################
Data Structures
1   Lists
	A matrix is a two dimensional list. Is a matrix a thing in python?
	Contained in square brackets.
	Initialize a list of 100 zeros with [0]*100
	Concatenate two lists with a '+' sign.
	Items in a list can be different types.
	'list(range(1, 10, 2))' will produce '[1, 3, 5, 7, 9]'.
	'print(list("hello world"))' will 
	    produce '['h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o', ' ', 'w', 'o', 'r', 'l', 'd']'.

******************************************************************************
2   Accessing List Items
    Print the nth item in a list with 'print(list_name{n - 1])
	Change the nth item in a list with list_name[n - 1] = item_value;
    	(item_value needs quotes if it's a string).
	Slice a list the same way you slice a string.
	    list_name[0: 3] will return '[first_list_item, second_list_item]'.
		Quotes aren't included; square brackets are.
		You can also include a step size. Step size can be negative.
		Step size of -1 will return the list in reverse order.
		The syntax is list_name[first_included_element, first_not_included_element, step-size].
		Like string you can leave out any indices.

******************************************************************************
3   Unpacking Lists
    To get a single item value from a list we would do:
	    variable_name = list_name[item_index]
	To unpack a list we do:
	    first_var, second_var, third_var,...,last_var = list_name.
		There must be as many vars as there are items in the list or we get
    		this error: 'ValueError: too many values to unpack'.
	If we only want some of the listwe could give variable names for the first
        few items then pack the rest of the list into a new sub-list:
        'first, second, *sub_list = original_list' gives:
		first is original_list[0],
		second is original_list[1] and
		sub_list is '[[original_list[2],original_list[3],...,original_list[-1]]'
		see the example code (C:\Users\Dave\Desktop\Mosh\python\5 - Data Structures\examples...) for more.
	
